04818nam a22005655i 9780889205628DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20061996xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892056287 a10.51644/97808892056282doi  a(DE-B1597)667833  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a266/.2/0922211 aWaugh, Earle H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDissonant Worlds :bRoger Vandersteene among the Cree /cEarle H. Waugh. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (376 p.) :b28 illustrations, 8 in full colour  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tRoger (Rogier) Vandersteene, 1918-1976 -- tMap -- tIntroduction -- tFlemish Matrix: Blood, Art and Piety -- t"Steentje's" Beginnings: Between Family and Flanders -- tGrouard before Vandersteene: Cree, Catholic, Canadian -- t"My Little Sisters, My Little Brothers": From Encounter to Wabasca -- tIntransigent Reality: Manitou's Land, Manitou's Children -- tThe Great Mystery: Visible and Touchable in Art -- tSojourn Charts: Poetry in Serenity and Flux -- tWrestling the Spirits: Powagan, Beethoven, Cancer -- tBeyond the Dissonance: Legacy of a Quest -- tTheoretical Epilogue: Vandersteene and the Understanding of Religion -- tChronology of Roger (Rogier) Vandersteene's Life -- tEvaluations of Vandersteene Collected during Research -- tOde to Vandersteene -- tNames of Informants -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow did a Belgian Oblate missionary who came to Canada to convert the aboriginals come to be buried as a Cree chief? In Dissonant Worlds Earle Waugh traces the remarkable career of Roger Vandersteene: his life as an Oblate missionary among the Cree, his intensive study of the Cree language and folkways, his status as a Cree medicine man, and the evolution of his views on the relationship between aboriginal traditions and the Roman Catholicism of the missionaries who worked among them. Above all, Dissonant Worlds traces Vandersteene’s quest to build a new religious reality: a strong, spiritually powerful Cree church, a magnificent Cree formulation of Christian life. In the wilderness of northern Canada Vandersteene found an aboriginal spirituality that inspired his own poetic and artistic nature and encouraged him to pursue a religious vision that united Cree tradition and Catholicism, one that constituted a dramatic revision of contemporary Catholic ritual. Through his paintings, poetry and liturgical modifications, Vandersteene attempted to recreate Cree reality and provide images grounded in Cree spirituality. Dissonant Worlds, in telling the story of Vandersteene’s struggle to integrate European Catholicism and aboriginal spirituality, raises the larger issue: Is there a place for missionary work in the modern church? It will be of interest to students of Native studies, the religious history of the Oblates, Canadian studies and Catholicism in the mid-twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCree IndiansxMissionszAlberta. 0aMissionarieszAlbertaxBiography. 0aMissionarieszBelgiumxBiography. 4aHistory: Canadian History. 4aIndigenous Studies. 4aReligion. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aVermandere, Willem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920562840uhttps://www.